<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Crocodile Dundee Calls It a G'Day: Paul Hogan has thrown his last shrimp on the 
barbie. 
</P>
<P>
The Australian star of the " 'Crocodile' Dundee" films has decided he's tired 
of saying "G'day" to the world and inviting tourists to visit Down Under for a 
bit of outdoor seafood dining. The Australian Tourist Commission said Friday 
the former Sydney Harbor Bridge riggerhad quit the television commercials shown 
all over the world. The Hogan commercials lured an estimated 250,000 Americans 
to Australia since they began in 1984. They'll be withdrawn from American 
television screens on March 13. BETH KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Paul Hogan 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
