<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: SCIENCE / MEDICINE; 
</P>
<P>
FANTASIES ABOUT LIFE, NATURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Thomas H. Maugh II, Times science writer Thomas H. Maugh II reports from New 
Orleans at the meeting of the American Assn. for the Advancement of Science. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Modern fantasies about early native Americans living in harmony with nature are 
just that -- fantasies, according to anthropologist Timothy Kohler of 
Washington State University. He has found that the prehistoric Anasazi of 
northwestern New Mexico and southwestern Colorado significantly altered the 
plant and animal mixes near their settlements. 
</P>
<P>
The effect on the environment occurred through wood harvesting for fuel and 
construction, field clearing and burning. This slash-and-burn strategy was 
initially successful, Kohler said, leading to population growth, but eventually 
populations became too dense to support this land-intensive agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
Kohler suggested that human impact on the environment in the Dolores 
Archeological Project area in southwestern Colorado eventually caused the 
residents to leave the area after a 300-year occupation. Residents had to move 
elsewhere to get enough to eat, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
